{"abstract": "There may be a billion people on Facebook, says Jeff Gibbard, but no business needs to reach a billion people.", "web_url": "https://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/15/a-social-media-marketer-assesses-facebooks-advertising-platform/", "snippet": "There may be a billion people on Facebook, says Jeff Gibbard, but no business needs to reach a billion people.", "lead_paragraph": "A guide we just published discusses ways small businesses can make the most of Facebook\u2019s revamped advertising programs. {"abstract": "The Greeks never figured this out, but perhaps you can. How can you determine the value of pi using two steel balls?", "lead_paragraph": "This coming Friday, 3.14 is Pi Day. Let\u2019s celebrate math\u2019s favorite number with a remarkable puzzle suggested several years ago by Alon Amit of Origami Logic. Dr. Amit and I were sitting on a couch in the old Palo Alto Facebook headquarters (Dr. Amit was working there at the time) surrounded by frenzy (the film \u201cThe Social Network\u201d had just been released) when he told me something amazing: someone had recently figured out a completely original way to calculate pi. It was also a remarkably simple method, requiring just two balls and a wall. {"abstract": "Deutsche Bank reports third-quarter earnings and management shake-up. | Facebook plans to increase spending. | The Fed is expected to end its bond-buying program. | A lesson on saying \u201cno\u201d to a hostile bid.", "web_url": "https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/29/morning-agenda-shake-up-at-deutsche-bank/", "snippet": "Deutsche Bank reports third-quarter earnings and management shake-up. | Facebook plans to increase spending. | The Fed is expected to end its bond-buying program. | A lesson on saying \u201cno\u201d to a hostile bid.", "lead_paragraph": "A day after announcing a management shuffle, Deutsche Bank reported on Wednesday that it had a net loss of about $117 million in the third quarter as it set aside more money to cover costs stemming from accusations of wrongdoing by its employees, Jack Ewing reports in DealBook. Profit in the quarter had been expected to suffer after Deutsche Bank, Germany\u2019s largest bank, said last week that it had set aside an additional 894 million euros, or about $1.1 billion, to cover legal costs. The loss provides another reminder that Deutsche Bank and other large investment banks are still preoccupied with dealing with the excesses associated with the financial crisis, as well as increasing demands from regulators intent on curbing risk-taking by banks.", "source": "The New York Times", "multimedia": [], "headline": {"main": "Morning Agenda: Shake-Up at Deutsche Bank", "kicker": "DealBook", "content_kicker": null, "print_headline": "", "name": null, "seo": null, "sub": null}, "keywords": [], "pub_date": "2014-10-29T11:44:38+0000", "document_type": "article", "news_desk": "Business", "section_name": "Business Day", "byline": {"original": "By Sydney Ember", "person": [{"firstname": "Sydney", "middlename": null, "lastname": "Ember", "qualifier": null, "title": null, "role": "reported", "organization": "", "rank": 1}], "organization": null}, "type_of_material": "News", "_id": "nyt://article/79ec6ee0-cdba-519f-8c75-c2ebc7e6d0c7", "word_count": 2099, "uri": "nyt://article/79ec6ee0-cdba-519f-8c75-c2ebc7e6d0c7"}

{"abstract": "Dan Bischof, ably assisted by \u2014 wait for it \u2014 Jeff Chen, makes his New York Times crossword debut.", "web_url": "https://wordplay.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/09/27/toy-story-boy/", "snippet": "Dan Bischof, ably assisted by \u2014 wait for it \u2014 Jeff Chen, makes his New York Times crossword debut.", "lead_paragraph": "MONDAY PUZZLE \u2014 I first heard the term \u201csupervocalics\u201d in a Facebook group for word lovers, and have been fascinated by the concept ever since. A supervocalic is a word or phrase that uses all of the vowels \u2014 A, E, I, O, and U but not Y \u2014 exactly once (note that \u201csupervocalic\u201d itself is one such word). A eurysupervocalic, as proposed by writer Eric Chaikin, is a word or phrase that uses all of the vowels, including Y, exactly once (although the word \u201ceurysupervocalic\u201d itself fails the test because of the repeated \u2018u\u2019).
